## 10. QMD Sidecar Integration

**Source file:** `src/memory/backend-config.ts`

QMD is a local-first search sidecar that combines BM25 + vector + learned reranking via a standalone CLI binary. The codebase configures it through `ResolvedQmdConfig`.

### Three search modes

| Mode | Command | Speed | Quality | When to use |
|------|---------|-------|---------|-------------|
| `search` | `qmd search --json` | Fast | Good | Default for interactive use |
| `vsearch` | `qmd vsearch --json` | Fast | Vector-only | When keywords add noise |
| `query` | `qmd query --json` | Slow (CPU-bound) | Best | Batch/offline use, best recall |

**Warning from the code comments:** `query` mode triggers query expansion + neural reranking, which can be "extremely slow on CPU-only systems." Default is `search` for this reason.

### Collection layout

QMD collections map to filesystem paths with glob patterns:

```typescript
// Auto-generated default collections:
{ name: "memory-root-{agentId}", path: workspaceDir, pattern: "MEMORY.md" }
{ name: "memory-alt-{agentId}",  path: workspaceDir, pattern: "memory.md" }
{ name: "memory-dir-{agentId}",  path: memory/, pattern: "**/*.md" }

// User-defined custom collections:
{ name: "docs-{agentId}",        path: ~/notes/, pattern: "**/*.md" }
```

Collection names are sanitized (lowercase, hyphens only) and deduplicated with numeric suffixes. Scoping by agent ID prevents cross-agent index contamination when multiple agents share the same QMD instance.

### Update cadence

```
Boot:     qmd update + qmd embed (background by default; waitForBootSync = true to block)
Interval: qmd update every 5 minutes (configurable)
Embed:    qmd embed every 60 minutes (separate from update; expensive)
Debounce: 15 seconds after file change before triggering update
```

**Guideline:** Keep `waitForBootSync = false` in production to avoid blocking chat startup. Accept slightly stale results for the first few seconds.

### Scope: preventing memory leak to group chats

Default QMD scope: deny all, allow only direct chats.

```json5
scope: {
  default: "deny",
  rules: [{ action: "allow", match: { chatType: "direct" } }]
}
```

This prevents personal memories from being injected into group channel conversations. Always scope memory recall to private/DM contexts unless you explicitly intend group recall.

